The shrine enshrines the war dead from Yamaguchi Prefecture who perished in national crises since the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新}}. This includes notable figures such as {{ill|Yoshida Shoin|ja|吉田松陰}}, {{ill|Kusaka Genzui|ja|久坂玄瑞}}, {{ill|Kijima Matabei|ja|来島又兵衛}}, {{ill|Omura Masujiro|ja|大村益次郎}}, {{ill|Takasugi Shinsaku|ja|高杉晋作}}, and {{ill|Gessho|ja|月性}}.

After {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦}}, Self-Defense Force personnel from Yamaguchi Prefecture who died in the line of duty have also been enshrined.

== History ==
In 1903 (Meiji 36), the {{ill|Bocho Yasukenkai|ja|防長靖献会}} was established in Yamaguchi Prefecture, and memorial services were held at the Sakura Batake parade ground (now the training ground for the {{ill|Japan Ground Self-Defense Force|ja|陸上自衛隊}} {{ill|Yamaguchi Garrison|ja|山口駐屯地}}) adjacent to the current location.

In 1939 (Showa 14), it was decided to establish a Gokoku Shrine in Yamaguchi Prefecture. The shrine was completed at its current location in August 1941 (Showa 16). It was designated as an Interior Minister-designated Gokoku Shrine, and on November 26 of the same year, 7159 spirits from Yamaguchi Prefecture who were enshrined at {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|ja|靖国神社}} were transferred here. The enshrinement ceremony was held on November 27.

== Location Information ==
; address
: Yamaguchi Prefecture, Yamaguchi City, Hirano 2-2-1
; Transportation
: Railway
: {{ill|Yamaguchi Station (Yamaguchi Prefecture)|ja|山口駅}} ({{ill|West Japan Railway Company|ja|西日本旅客鉄道}} (JR West) {{ill|Yamaguchi Line|ja|山口線}}) - 10 minutes by car

== Surroundings ==
* {{ill|Ima Hachiman Shrine|ja|今八幡宮}}
* {{ill|Jouei-ji Temple (Yamaguchi City)|ja|常栄寺}}
* {{ill|Toei Shrine and Noda Shrine|ja|豊榮神社・野田神社}}
* {{ill|Saikotei|ja|山口市菜香亭}}
