'''Yamaguchi Prefecture Gokoku Shrine'''（山口縣護國神社{{ill|Yamaguchi Prefecture Gokoku Shrine|ja|山口縣護國神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}）is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Gokoku Shrine|ja|護国神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) located in {{ill|Yamaguchi City|ja|山口市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yamaguchi Prefecture|ja|山口県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines the war dead from Yamaguchi Prefecture who perished in national crises since the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. This includes notable figures such as {{ill|Yoshida Shoin|ja|吉田松陰|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kusaka Genzui|ja|久坂玄瑞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kijima Matabei|ja|来島又兵衛|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Omura Masujiro|ja|大村益次郎|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Takasugi Shinsaku|ja|高杉晋作|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Gessho|ja|月性|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

After {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Self-Defense Force personnel from Yamaguchi Prefecture who died in the line of duty have also been enshrined.

== History ==
In 1903 (Meiji 36), the {{ill|Bocho Yasukenkai|ja|防長靖献会|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was established in Yamaguchi Prefecture, and memorial services were held at the Sakura Batake parade ground (now the training ground for the {{ill|Japan Ground Self-Defense Force|ja|陸上自衛隊|qq=draft|qq=draft}} {{ill|Yamaguchi Garrison|ja|山口駐屯地|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) adjacent to the current location.

In 1939 (Showa 14), it was decided to establish a Gokoku Shrine in Yamaguchi Prefecture. The shrine was completed at its current location in August 1941 (Showa 16). It was designated as an Interior Minister-designated Gokoku Shrine, and on November 26 of the same year, 7159 spirits from Yamaguchi Prefecture who were enshrined at {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|ja|靖国神社|1=Yasukuni Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were transferred here. The enshrinement ceremony was held on November 27.

